        <div xml:id="AN8-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN8">
            <lg type="edition"><l>īyaṟ puṟṟat tīrmpuṟat tiṟutta</l>
<l>kurumpi valcip peruṅkai <choice><seg>yēṟṟai</seg><seg>yēṟṟait</seg></choice></l>
<l>tūṅkutōṟ ṟutiya vaḷḷukirk kāliṟ</l>
<l>pāmpumata ṉaḻiyum pāṉāṭ kaṅkulu</l>
<l>mariya valla ma<supplied>ṉi</supplied>ku<supplied>ḷai</supplied> periya</l>
<l>kēḻa laṭṭa pēḻvā yēṟṟaip</l>
<l>palāvama laṭukkam pulāa vīrkkuṅ</l>
<l><choice><seg>kaḻaiñaral</seg><seg>kaḻainaral</seg></choice> cilampi ṉāṅkaṇ vaḻaiyoṭu</l>
<l>vāḻai yōṅkiya tāḻkaṇ ṇacumpiṟ</l>
<l>paṭukaṭuṅ kaḷiṟṟiṉ varuttañ coliya<supplied>p</supplied></l>
<l>piṭiyaṭi <choice><seg>murukkiya</seg><seg>nerukkiya</seg></choice> perumarap pūcal</l>
<l>viṇṭōy viṭarakat tiyampu mavarnāṭ</l>
<l>ṭeṇṇarum piṟaṅkaṉ māṉatar mayaṅkātu</l>
<l>miṉṉuviṭac ciṟiya votuṅki <choice><seg>meṉmelat</seg><seg>meṉmeṟ</seg></choice></l>
<l><choice><seg>tuḷitalait</seg><seg>ṟuḷitalait</seg></choice> talaiiya maṇiyē raimpāl</l>
<l>ciṟupuṟam <choice><seg>putaiiya</seg><seg>putaiya</seg></choice> vārik kuralpiḻiyūu</l>
<l>neṟikeṭa <choice><seg>vilaṅki</seg><seg>vilaṅkiya</seg></choice> <choice><seg>nīyi</seg><seg>nīi</seg></choice> riccura</l>
<l>maṟitalu maṟitirō veṉṉunarp peṟiṉē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Even the midnights, when the snake’s strength perishes</l>
<l rend="indent">	under the sharp-clawed foot sheathed in hanging skin</l>
<l rend="indent">	of the big-handed male [ant-eater] whose food are ants’ combs</l>
<l rend="indent">	broken from the wet back of the white ant hill,</l>
<l>would not be so difficult, friend,</l>
<l>– if one were to obtain someone who said [to him]:</l>
<l>“retreating a little, while flashes are emitted,</l>
<l>without being confused on the roads of the deer among the hills hard to count</l>
<l>in his land,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where inside the sky-touching caves resounds</l>
<l rend="indent">	the noise of big trees crushed by the foot of the elephant cow</l>
<l rend="indent">	in order to alleviate the suffering of the fierce elephant bull that has fallen</l>
<l rend="indent">	into a mud hole in a low spot grown high with plantains</l>
<l rend="indent">	and Gamboge,</l>
<l rend="indent">	there on the mountain side rustling with bamboo,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where the large-mouthed male [tiger] that killed a big boar</l>
<l rend="indent">	drags the flesh over the mountain flank thick with jack trees,</l>
<l>you, going astray when the path gets lost,</l>
<l rend="indent">	will you really know this desert,</l>
<l>after you combed, so that the small of [her] back is buried, smoothing out [her] curls,</l>
<l>[her hair] in five parts, resembling sapphires that have been offered drops on top,<note place="foot">tuḷi talai talaiiya: the meaning of this phrase is not clear.  Is the idea that water enhances the glow of the jewel?</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	very softly?”</l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
